{"title_page": "1975 Oklahoma Sooners football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=1975\n  |team=Oklahoma Sooners\n  |image=\n  |image_size=100px\n  |conference=Big Eight Conference\n  |division=\n  |short_conf=Big 8\n  |CoachRank=1\n  |APRank=1\n  |record=11&ndash;1\n  |conf_record=6&ndash;1\n  |head_coach=[[Barry Switzer]]\n  |hc_year=3rd\n  |off_coach=[[Galen Hall]]\n  |oc_year=3rd\n  |def_coach=[[Larry Lacewell]]\n  |dc_year=6th\n  |off_scheme=[[Wishbone formation|Wishbone]]\n  |def_scheme=[[5\u20132 defense|5\u20132]]\n  |stadium=[[Oklahoma Memorial Stadium]] (Capacity: 71,187)\n  |champion=Consensus national champion<br>Big Eight co-champion<br>Orange Bowl champion\n  |bowl=[[1976 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n  |bowl_result=  W 14\u20136 vs. [[1975 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n}}\n{{1975 Big 8 football standings}}\nThe '''1975 Oklahoma Sooners football team''' represented the [[University of Oklahoma]] in the [[1975 NCAA Division I football season]]. The team was helmed by [[Barry Switzer]] in his third season as head coach. After sailing through their first eight games, Oklahoma suffered a surprising home loss to [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]], which snapped a 28-game winning streak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/football_records/DI/2009/2009FBS.pdf|title=2009 Division I Football Records Book: Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) Records|accessdate=July 9, 2010|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|page=96}}</ref>  With only two regular season games and a bowl trip left, any hopes for a repeat [[NCAA Division I FBS National Football Championship|national championship]] looked slim. \n \nOU defeated [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]], 28&ndash;27, in [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia]] before coming home to defeat second-ranked [[1975 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]], 35&ndash;10 to take the [[Big 8 Conference]] title. With the conference title in tow, the No. 3&ndash;ranked Sooners, in their first bowl game under Switzer, headed to the [[1976 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] to meet [[1975 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]. \n \nOU prevailed in that game with a 14&ndash;6 victory and got pushed to the top spot in the polls when both #1 [[1975 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] and #2 [[1975 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] suffered defeats in their bowl games. Oklahoma won its 27th conference and fifth national championship.<ref name=\"1975 Oklahoma Sooners\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-1975-national-champs.html|title=1975 National Champions|work=SoonerSports.com|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma|University of Oklahoma Athletic Department]]|accessdate=August 21, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718200705/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-1975-national-champs.html|archivedate=2007-07-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Sooners served their third season of NCAA probation in 1975. They were banned from appearing on television during the regular season, but the portion of the probation banning them from bowl games was lifted (Oklahoma did not play in a bowl game in 1973, but appeared twice on television; it was banned from both television and bowl games in 1974). Oklahoma returned to television for the Orange Bowl.\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1975\n| poll = AP\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 13\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 1\n| opponent = [[1975 Oregon Webfoots football team|Oregon]]\n| site_stadium = [[Oklahoma Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Norman, Oklahoma|Norman, OK]]\n| tv = \n| score = 62\u20137\n| attend = 70,213<ref name=\"stats\">http://www.soonerstats.com/football/seasons/schedule.cfm?seasonid=1975</ref>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 20\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 1\n| opponent = [[1975 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh]]\n| opprank = 15\n| site_stadium = Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n| site_cityst = Norman, OK\n| tv = \n| score = 46\u201310\n| attend = 71,030<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 26\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| rank = 1\n| opponent = [[1975 Miami Hurricanes football team|Miami (FL)]]\n| site_stadium = [[Miami Orange Bowl]]\n| site_cityst = [[Miami|Miami, FL]]\n| tv = \n| score = 20\u201317\n| attend = 39,020<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 4\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 1\n| opponent = [[1975 Colorado Buffaloes football team|Colorado]]\n| opprank = 2\n| site_stadium = Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n| site_cityst = Norman, OK\n| tv = \n| score = 21\u201320\n| attend = 71,118<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 11\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| neutral = y\n| rank = 2\n| opponent = [[1975 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]]\n| opprank = 5\n| gamename = [[Red River Rivalry|Red River Shootout]]\n| site_stadium = [[Cotton Bowl (stadium)|Cotton Bowl]]\n| site_cityst = [[Dallas|Dallas, TX]]\n| tv = \n| score = 24\u201317\n| attend = 72,032<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 18\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 2\n| opponent = [[1975 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State]]\n| site_stadium = [[KSU Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Manhattan, Kansas|Manhattan, KS]]\n| tv = \n| score = 25\u20133\n| attend = 33,196<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 25\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 2\n| opponent = [[1975 Iowa State Cyclones football team|Iowa State]]\n| site_stadium = Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n| site_cityst = Norman, OK\n| tv = \n| score = 39\u20137\n| attend = 70,879<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 1\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 1\n| opponent = [[1975 Oklahoma State Cowboys football team|Oklahoma State]]\n| opprank = 19\n| gamename = [[Bedlam Series]]\n| site_stadium = [[Lewis Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Stillwater, Oklahoma|Stillwater, OK]]\n| tv = \n| score = 27\u20137\n| attend = 49,358<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 8\n| w/l = l\n| rank = 2\n| opponent = [[1975 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]]\n| site_stadium = Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n| site_cityst = Norman, OK\n| tv = \n| score = 3\u201323\n| attend = 70,922<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 15\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = 6\n| opponent = [[1975 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]]\n| opprank = 18\n| gamename = [[Missouri\u2013Oklahoma football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Faurot Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia, MO]]\n| tv = \n| score = 28\u201327\n| attend = 67,518<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 22\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 7\n| opponent = [[1975 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]]\n| opprank = 2\n| gamename = [[Nebraska\u2013Oklahoma football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n| site_cityst = Norman, OK\n| tv = \n| score = 35\u201310\n| attend = 71,952<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = January 1, 1976\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| neutral = y\n| rank = 3\n| opponent = [[1975 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n| opprank = 5\n| gamename = [[1976 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]\n| site_stadium = Miami Orange Bowl\n| site_cityst = Miami, FL\n| tv = [[NBC Sports|NBC]]\n| score = 14\u20136\n| attend = 76,799<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n}}\n}}<ref name=\"1975 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soonerstats.com/football/seasons/schedule.cfm?SeasonID=1975|title=1975 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule|publisher=Soonerstats.com|year=2007|accessdate=April 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:85%;\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\"|'''Complete Roster of 1975 season''' \n|-\n|valign=\"