e DB \u2013 ''Sophomore''\n* Mike Pleasant DB \u2013 ''Sophomore''\n* Mike Babb DHB \u2013 ''Freshman''\n*1 Zac Henderson FS \u2013 ''Sophomore''\n*27 Jerry Reese FS \u2013 ''Junior''\n*21 Sidney Brown LCB \u2013 ''Junior''\n*26 Frank Rohr LCB \u2013 ''Sophomore''\n*16 Terry Peters RCB \u2013 ''Sophomore''\n*31 Eric Van Camp RCB \u2013 ''Senior''\n*15 Mike Birks SS \u2013 ''Senior''\n*7 Scott Hill SS \u2013 ''Junior''\n*8 Myron Shoate SS \u2013 ''Sophomore''\n\n'''Kickers'''\n\n*3 Tony DiRienzo K \u2013 ''Senior''\n*33 Bill Shirk K \u2013 ''Sophomore''\n* [[Uwe von Schamann]] K \u2013 ''Freshman''\n\n|-\n|colspan=\"50\" align=\"center\"|<small>\u2020 Starter at position&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;* Injured; did not play in 1975.\nCourtesy of [http://www.soonerstats.com/football/players/roster.cfm?seasonid=1975 Soonerstats.com]</small>\n|}\n\n==Game summaries==\nOklahoma had won the AP National Title in 1974 and began the year by thrashing Oregon 62-7 in Norman.  OU played host to a [[Johnny Majors]] coached #15 Pittsburgh squad, sporting junior running back sensation [[Tony Dorsett]] (only a year away from the [[Heisman trophy]] and the collegiate rushing record), and they dominated, outscoring the Panthers 46&ndash;10. But a trip to unranked Miami was nearly fatal.  The Sooners scored all 20 of their points in the second quarter and finished with just 163 rushing yards and 176 total, barely surviving a ten&ndash;point Hurricanes' fourth quarter en route to a 20&ndash;17 victory. That win was not enough to knock the Sooners to the second spot in the polls, but a one-point win over Colorado the following week was. Against the Buffaloes, the vaunted Sooner wishbone offense looked abysmal, and they surrendered a 14&ndash;point lead in the second half. A botched CU extra point in the final 79 seconds proved the difference. [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] took over the number one ranking. The Sooners, despite the close calls, came into Dallas atop a 24&ndash;game winning streak and a 33-game unbeaten streak and ranked #2 in the country.<ref name=\"1975 Oklahoma Season\">{{cite web|url=http://soonerstats.com/football/games/recap.cfm?GameID=731|title=Beginning of Oklahoma Sooners 1975 Football Season|publisher=Soonerstats.com|year=2007|accessdate=May 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Oregon===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Oregon\n|V1=7 |V2=0 |V3=0 |V4=0\n|Host=Oklahoma\n|H1=10 |H2=33 |H3= 7|H4=12\n|Date=September 13\n|Location=[[Oklahoma Memorial Stadium]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=70,213\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Pittsburgh===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Pittsburgh\n|V1= 0|V2=0 |V3= 3|V4=7\n|Host=Oklahoma\n|H1= 7|H2=16 |H3=7 |H4=16\n|Date=September 20\n|Location=Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Miami (FL)===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Oklahoma\n|V1=0 |V2= 20|V3= 0|V4=0\n|Host=Miami (FL)\n|H1=7 |H2= 0|H3=0 |H4=10\n|Date=September 26\n|Location=[[Orange Bowl (stadium)|Orange Bowl]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=39,020\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Colorado===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Colorado\n|V1= 0|V2=7 |V3= 7|V4=6\n|Host=Oklahoma\n|H1=7 |H2= 7|H3=7 |H4=0\n|Date=October 4\n|Location=Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=71,118\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry |FirstEntry=yes |Quarter=Q1 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Washington 11 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OKLA 7\u20130 |LastEntry=}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry |FirstEntry= |Quarter=Q2 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Washington 74 yard punt return (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OKLA 14\u20130 |LastEntry=}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry |FirstEntry= |Quarter=Q2 |Time= |Team=COL |Event=Waddy 3 yard run (Mackenzie kick) |Score=OKLA 14\u20137 |LastEntry=}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry |FirstEntry= |Quarter= Q3|Time= |Team=COL |Event=Williams 1 yard run (Mackenzie kick) |Score=Tie 14\u201314 |LastEntry=}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry |FirstEntry= |Quarter= Q3|Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Peacock 2 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OKLA 21\u201314 |LastEntry=}}\n{{AFB game box scoring entry |FirstEntry= |Quarter= Q4 |Time=1:23 |Team=COL |Event=Waddy 8 yard pass from Williams (kick failed) |Score=OKLA 21\u201320 |LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n<ref>Eugene Register-Guard. 1975 Oct 5. Retrieved 2018-Nov-09.</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n===Texas===\n{{See also|Red River Rivalry}}\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=#2 Oklahoma vs. #5 Texas\n|Visitor=Oklahoma\n|V1=10 |V2=0 |V3=7 |V4=7\n|Host=#5 Texas\n|H1=0 |H2=7 |H3= 0|H4=10\n|Date=October 11\n|Location=[[Cotton Bowl (stadium)|Cotton Bowl]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=72,032\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=<!--NONE (Oklahoma banned from television due to NCAA probation)-->\n}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |FirstEntry=yes |Quarter=Q1 |Time= |Team= OKLA |Event= DiRienzo 45 yard field goal|Score= OKLA 3-0 }}    \n{{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q1 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Phillips recovered fumble in end zone (DiRienzo kick) |Score= OKLA 10-0 }}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q1 |Time= |Team=TEX|Event=Jackson 38 yard pass from Akins (Erxleben kick) |Score= OKLA 10-7}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q3 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=[[Joe Washington|Washington]] 9 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OU 17-7}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry  |Quarter= Q4|Time= |Team=TEX |Event=Walker 25 yard run (Erxleben kick) |Score=OKLA 17-14}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter= Q4|Time= |Team= TEX|Event=Erxleben 43 yard field goal |Score=Tie 17-17}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q4 |Time= |Team= OKLA |Event=Ivory 33 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OKLA 24-17 |LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=mq6pegT_rlEC&dat=19751012&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"Oklahoma Outlasts Rugged Heat, Texas.\" Palm Beach Post. October 12, 1975]</ref>\n\nTexas came into Dallas with a bona fide superstar in 225&ndash;pound sophomore fullback [[Earl Campbell]].  The fearsome runner had trampled everything in his path en route to 508 yards (8.1 ypc), including 198 yards against [[1975 Washington Huskies football team|Washington]].  Behind the young Campbell, the Longhorns were leading the nation in rushing, total offense and scoring, averaging 44 points per game.\n\nThe Sooners had a leader in [[Steve Davis (quarterback)|Steve Davis]], an ordained minister that could run and pass.  The halfbacks, Joe Washington and Horace Ivory were speedy and elusive.  The receiving corps, paced by Senior Billy Brooks, was among the best of the wishbone era at OU.  Of course, the greatest asset to the Sooners was not on offense.  The 1975 OU defense was among the very best in a storied history, led by [[Lee Roy Selmon]], who would go on to win both the [[Outland Trophy]] and the [[Lombardi Award]] as the nation's best lineman.\n\nIt was the Sooner defense that made the Longhorns lose a fifth straight Red River Shootout.  Neither offense exploded with big plays, both scoring hard fought points in the red zone.  The game was best characterized by the hard hitting from both sides, which led to a considerable number of turnovers.  The Longhorns fumbled the ball four times and gave away an interception.  The Sooners lost two fumbles.  The Sooner defense proved its mettle against the powerful Campbell, holding him to 95 yards on 23 carries.  Although he was the game's leading ball carrier, he also marked the 21st straight time that a team failed to have a 100&ndash;yard rusher against the Sooners.  The Sooners prevailed 24&ndash;17.<ref name=\"1975 Oklahoma-Texas Game\">{{cite web|url=http://soonerstats.com/football/games/recap.cfm?GameID=731|title=1975 OU-Texas Game|publisher=Soonerstats.com|year=2007|accessdate=May 17, 2007}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Kansas State===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Oklahoma\n|V1= 14|V2= 3|V3=5 |V4=3\n|Host=Kansas St\n|H1= 0|H2= 3|H3= 0|H4=0\n|Date=October 18\n|Location=[[KSU Stadium]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=33,196\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Iowa State===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=Iowa State at #2 Oklahoma\n|Visitor=Iowa St\n|V1=0 |V2= 0|V3=7 |V4=0\n|Host= Oklahoma\n|H1=17 |H2=9 |H3=7 |H4=6\n|Date=October 25\n|Location=Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=70,879\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |FirstEntry=yes |Quarter=Q1 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=[[Joe Washington|Washington]] 3 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score= OKLA 7-0}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q1 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=[[Steve Davis (quarterback)|Davis]] 11 yard run (DiRienzio kick) |Score= OKLA 14-0}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q1 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=DiRienzio 31 yard field goal |Score= OKLA 17-0}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q2 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Safety |Score=OU 19-0 }}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q2 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Culbreath 8 yard run (DiRienzio kick) |Score= OKLA 26-0}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q3 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Washington 6 yard run (DiRienzio kick) |Score= OKLA 33-0}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q3|Time= |Team=ISU |Event=Wingender 13 yard run (Length kick) |Score= OKLA 33-7}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q4 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=[[Billy Sims|Sims]] 17 yard run (pass failed) |Score=OKLA 39-7 |LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}<ref>Eugene Register-Guard. October 26, 1975</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Kansas (November nightmare)===\nAfter thrashing Kansas State, Iowa State, and Oklahoma State by a combined score of 91&ndash;17, the Sooners returned home.  Inexplicably, a team that had run roughshod over equivalent teams, managed to suffer a 23&ndash;3 loss to unranked Kansas, a team that came into Norman with a 5&ndash;3 record.  The Sooners were caught flat and were upset by the Jayhawks, knocking them from the #2 spot in the polls down to #7.  In Columbia against #18 Missouri the following week, they needed a 71&ndash;yard touchdown run from Joe Washington on a critical fourth and one, a Washington run for a successful two&ndash;point conversion, and two missed field goal attempts by the Tigers in the final two minutes to eke out a 28&ndash;27 win.  The struggles took their toll, and OU found themselves down another spot in the poll heading into the annual showdown against Nebraska.  The defending national champs were reeling and in search of an identity.  No game could have had nearly as much on the line as the final regular season game for the Big 8 Championship.<ref name=\"1975 OU Season \u2013 November Nightmare\">{{cite web|url=http://soonerstats.com/football/games/recap.cfm?GameID=737|title=November Nightmare|publisher=Soonerstats.com|year=2007|accessdate=May 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Oklahoma State===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Oklahoma\n|V1= 10|V2=0 |V3=10 |V4=7\n|Host=Oklahoma St\n|H1= 0|H2=0 |H3=0 |H4=7\n|Date=November 1\n|Location=[[Lewis Field]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=49,358\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Kansas===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Kansas\n|V1=0 |V2= 7|V3=9 |V4=7\n|Host=Oklahoma\n|H1=3 |H2=0 |H3=0 |H4=0\n|Date=November 8\n|Location=Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=70,922\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Missouri===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=\n|Visitor=Oklahoma\n|V1=12 |V2=8 |V3=0 |V4=8\n|Host=Missouri\n|H1=0 |H2=0 |H3= 7|H4=20\n|Date=November 15\n|Location=[[Faurot Field|Memorial Stadium]]\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=67,518\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Nebraska===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title=#2 Nebraska at #7 Oklahoma\n|Visitor=Nebraska\n|V1= 3|V2=0 |V3= 7|V4=0\n|Host=Oklahoma\n|H1=0 |H2=7 |H3=7 |H4=21\n|Date=November 22\n|Location=Oklahoma Memorial Stadium\n|StartTime=\n|TimeZone=\n|ElapsedTime=\n|Attendance=70,286\n|Weather=\n|Referee=\n|TVAnnouncers=\n|TVStation=<!--NONE (Oklahoma banned from television due to NCAA probation)-->\n}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |FirstEntry=yes |Quarter= Q1|Time= |Team= NEB|Event=Coyle 24 yard field goal |Score=NEB 3-0}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q2 |Time= |Team= OKLA|Event=[[Steve Davis (quarterback)|Davis]] 1 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OKLA 7-3}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter= Q3|Time= |Team=NEB |Event=Anthony 1 yard run (Coyle kick) |Score=NEB 10-7 }}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q3 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Ivory 5 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OKLA 14-10}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q4 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Peacock 3 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score=OKLA 21-10}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry  |Quarter=Q4 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=Davis 8 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score= OKLA 28-10}}\n    {{AFB Game Box Scoring Entry |Quarter=Q4 |Time= |Team=OKLA |Event=[[Billy Sims|Sims]] 4 yard run (DiRienzo kick) |Score= OKLA 35-10|LastEntry=yes}}\n{{AFB game box end}}<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=4pF9x-cDGsoC&dat=19751123&printsec=frontpage&hl=en \"Oklahoma rides fumbles to Miami.\" Eugene Register-Guard. November 23, 1975]</ref>\n\nNebraska began 1975 mostly under the radar, but they were riding a 10-0 record and sporting one of the best passing quarterbacks in the nation in Vince Ferragamo, who had transferred a season before from California.  He had completed 66 of 109 passes for 1,007 yards and 12 touchdowns, against only two interceptions. The Huskers had stepped into the #2 spot in the polls that the Sooners had vacated in their loss to Kansas.\n\nThe Cornhusker offense was balanced, averaging 265.6 yards rushing and 156.7 yards passing per game, and was among the nation's leaders in scoring, averaging 34.3 points per game.  The Nebraska defense was allowing only 8.5 points per game. They had posted four shutouts, including their last two opponents to run their string to ten consecutive scoreless quarters. The Black Shirt D had held the same Jayhawks team that had upset OU earlier in the season to only 177 yards of total offense.\n\nThe Big Eight title, as usual, was on the line in 1975. The winner would play in the Orange Bowl with a possible shot at a national championship. Oklahoma, realizing all that was on the line, had worked with Fiesta Bowl officials for a potential bid in Tempe if they lost to the Cornhuskers.  Nebraska had shunned the Fiesta officials, possibly shutting themselves out of the bowls in the event of a loss.\n\nUltimately, the Sooners came out of Norman with the conference title and the shot at a national title in the Orange Bowl, and it turned out to not even be close. Three turnovers in the fourth quarter had ended the Huskers' chances.  Oklahoma scored on all three to make it five touchdowns from six Nebraska turnovers. The Sooners came away with a convincing and incredible 25-point victory over the second-ranked team in the land.\n\nOnce again, it was the Oklahoma defense that made the big plays when they needed to and controlled the Nebraska offense, limiting them to 245 total yards, only 70 on the ground. Ferragamo, who came into the game with high expectations, had completed 13 of his 25 passes for 146 yards.  His four turnovers, however, had spoiled the game for Nebraska, and Oklahoma was on its way to face Michigan in the 1976 Orange Bowl.<ref name=\"1975 OU-Nebraska Game\">{{cite web|url=http://soonerstats.com/football/games/recap.cfm?GameID=737|title=OU-Nebraska Game 1975|publisher=Soonerstats.com|year=2007|accessdate=May 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Orange Bowl===\n{{Main|1976 Orange Bowl}}\n{{Seealso|1975 Michigan Wolverines football team}}\n{{Americanfootballbox\n|bg=\n|bg2=\n|titlestyle={{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Oklahoma Sooners|border=2}}; text-align:center\n|state=collapsed\n|title=Orange Bowl: #4 Michigan Wolverines vs. #2 Oklahoma Sooners (10\u20131)\n|date={{tooltip|January 1, 1976|Thursday}}\n|time=\n|road=[[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]]\n|R1=0 |R2= 0|R3=0 |R4=6\n|home='''[[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]]'''\n|H1=0 |H2=7 |H3=0 |H4=7\n|stadium=[[Orange Bowl (stadium)|Orange Bowl]], [[Miami, Florida]]\n|attendance=76,799\n|weather=\n|referee=\n|TV=[[College Football on NBC|NBC]]\n|TVAnnouncers=[[Jim Simpson (sportscaster)|Jim Simpson]] and [[John Brodie]]\n|reference=[https://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/bowls/1976orng.htm Recap/Box]\n|scoring=\n'''Second quarter'''\n*OU \u2013 [[Billy Brooks]] 39-yard run (Tony DiRienzo kick). ''Oklahoma 7\u20130. '''Drive:'''''\n'''Fourth quarter'''\n*OU \u2013 [[Steve Davis (quarterback)|Steve Davis]] 9-yard run (Tony DiRienzo kick). ''Oklahoma 14\u20130. '''Drive:'''''\n*MICH \u2013 [[Gordon Bell (American football)|Gordon Bell]] 2-yard run (run failed). ''Oklahoma 14\u20136. '''Drive:'''''\n|stats=\n;Top passers\n*MICH \u2013 [[Rick Leach (baseball)|Rick Leach]] \u2013 2/16, 33 yards, 3 INT\n*OU \u2013 [[Steve Davis (quarterback)|Steve Davis]] \u2013 3/5, 63 yards\n;Top rushers\n*MICH \u2013 Rick Leach \u2013 13 rushes, 62 yards\n*OU \u2013 [[Joe Washington]] \u2013 17 rushes, 73 yards\n;Top receivers\n*MICH \u2013 [[Gordon Bell (American football)|Gordon Bell]] \u2013 1 reception, 17 yards\n*OU \u2013 [[Tinker Owens]] \u2013 3 receptions, 63 yards\n}}\n\nUCLA upset top&ndash;ranked Ohio State earlier in the day, and Oklahoma knew that it had a chance for a national title in Barry Switzer's first bowl game as a head coach.  It wouldn't be easy.  The Wolverines were a punishing team, and made the Sooners know it early.  In the end, a 39&ndash;yard end around by Billy Brooks and a nine&ndash;yard keeper by [[Steve Davis (quarterback)|Steve Davis]] were enough for a 14&ndash;6 victory and a fifth national championship.<ref name=\"1976 Orange Bowl\">{{cite web|title=2006 Oklahoma Football Guide|work=SoonerSports.com|publisher=[[University of Oklahoma|University of Oklahoma Athletic Department]]|url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/2007-mfootbl-guide.html|accessdate=August 21, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718200724/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/2007-mfootbl-guide.html|archivedate=2007-07-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n===All-Americans===\n* [[Lee Roy Selmon]], [[Defensive tackle]] \n* [[Dewey Selmon]], [[Noseguard]] \n* Terry Webb, [[Offensive guard]]\n* Mike Vaughan, [[Offensive tackle]] \n* Billy Brooks, [[Wide receiver|Split end]]\n* [[Jimbo Elrod]], [[Defensive end]]  \n* Tinker Owens, Split end \n* [[Joe Washington]], [[Running back|Halfback]]\n\n===Individual award winners===\n* [[Lee Roy Selmon]] \u2013 [[Outland Trophy]], [[Lombardi Award]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{1975 Oklahoma Sooners football navbox}}\n{{Oklahoma Sooners football navbox}}\n{{College Football National Champion navbox}}\n{{Big Eight Conference football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1975 Big Eight Conference football season|Oklahoma Sooners]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Sooners football seasons]]\n[[Category:College football national champions]]\n[[Category:Big Eight Conference football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:Orange Bowl champion seasons]]\n[[Category:1975 in sports in Oklahoma|Sooner football]]\n", "name_user": "Bkell", "label": "safe", "comment": "hyphen", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1975_Oklahoma_Sooners_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Clothing laws by country", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=June 2008}}\n\n[[File:Poster of a public decency campaign in Qatar.png|thumb|200px|right|Poster in Qatar calling on foreign women to dress modestly]]\n[[Clothing]] laws vary considerably around the world. In general, in most countries, there are no laws which prescribe what clothing is required to be worn. However, the community standards of clothing are set indirectly by way of prosecution of those who wear something that is not socially approved. Those people who wear insufficient clothing can be prosecuted in many countries under various offences termed [[indecent exposure]], public indecency or other descriptions. Generally, these offences do not themselves define what is and what is not acceptable clothing to constitute the offence, and leave it to a judge to determine in each case.\n\nMost clothing laws concern which parts of the body must ''not'' be exposed to view; there are exceptions. Some countries have strict clothing laws, such as in some [[Islamic]] countries. Other countries are more tolerant of non-conventional attire and are relaxed about nudity.  Many countries have different laws and customs for men and women, what may be allowed or perceived often varies by gender.<ref Name=\"Kirby\">{{cite book\n  | last =Kirby\n  | first =Kathleen M. \n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title =Indifferent boundaries: spatial concepts of human subjectivity\n  | publisher =Guilford Press\n  | year =1996\n  | location =\n  | url =https://books.google.com/?id=Y4PcShmKe-YC&pg=PA132&dq=different+laws+for+men+and+women,+public+nudity+is+legal+on+most+beaches#PPA124,M1\n  | doi =\n  | isbn = 0-89862-572-6\n\n  | page = Chapter 5 }}</ref>\n\nSeparate laws are usually in place to regulate [[obscenity]], which includes certain depictions of people in various states of undress, and [[child pornography]], which may include similar photographs of children.\n\nIn some countries, non-sexual toplessness or nudity is legal. However, private or public establishments can establish a [[dress code]] which requires visitors to wear prescribed clothing.\n\nThere are a variety of laws around the world which affect what people can and cannot wear. For example, some laws require a person in authority to wear the appropriate uniform. For example, a police officer on duty may be required to wear a uniform; and it can be illegal for the general public to wear a police officer's uniform. The same could apply to firefighters and other emergency personnel. In some countries, for example in Australia, the [[Scouts Australia|boy scouts]] uniform is also protected.\n\nIn most [[Court|courts of law]], lawyers and judges are required by law or custom to wear [[Court Dress|court dress]], which may entail robes or traditional wigs.\n\nIn many countries, regulations require workers to wear protective clothing, such as [[safety helmet]]s, shoes, vests, etc., as appropriate. The obligation is generally on employers to ensure that their workers wear the appropriate protective clothing. Similarly, health regulations may require those who handle food to wear hair covering, gloves and other clothing.\n\nGovernments can also influence standards of dress shown on television through its licensing powers.\n\nIn addition to nude beaches and similar exceptional locations, there are some public events in which nudity is tolerated more than usual, such as the [[naked bike ride]]s held in several countries.\n\n== International laws and customs and culture ==\nThere are many specific circumstances where body parts have to be covered, often for safety or sanitary reasons.\n\nIn Saudi Arabia and Iran, women must conceal almost their entire bodies (see [[hijab]]).\n\n==Australia==\n\nIn [[Australia]], [[indecent exposure]] laws only refer to the genital area. However, many local councils impose their own rules, and have the power to ask topless people to leave an area.<ref name=Lifehackerau>{{cite news|title=Is it legal to sunbathe topless in Australia?|date=Nov 30, 2015|access-date= Nov 12, 2018|author=Chris Jager|publisher=Lifehacker|url=https://www.lifehacker.com.au/2015/11/is-it-legal-to-sunbathe-topless/}}</ref> Additionally, women who go topless are sometimes slapped with more vague charges such as being a public nuisance, or offensive behaviour.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=How to Legally #FreeTheNipple in Australia|date=March 11, 2016|access-date= Nov 12, 2018|author=Katherine Gillespie|magazine=Vice.com|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_au/article/mbv4pb/how-to-legally-freethenipple-in-australia}}</ref>\n\nOn public beaches, local bylaws are not heavily enforced, and women can often sunbathe topless without fuss.<ref name=Lifehackerau></ref>\n\nBreastfeeding in public places is a legal right in Australia. Under the [[Sex Discrimination Act 1984]], no business or service provider can discriminate against a breastfeeding woman.<ref>{{cite article|url=https://www.breastfeeding.asn.au/bf-info/breastfeeding-and-law/legalright|title=Breastfeeding in public - your legal rights|date=Aug 2016|access-date=12 Nov 2018|publisher=Australian Breastfeeding Association}}</ref>\n\n==Brazil==\nEver since 1940, in the Title VI of the Penal Code, naming crimes against sexual dignity (until 2009 crimes against [social] conventions), the fourth chapter is dedicated to a crime named \"public outrage [related] to modesty\" ({{lang-pt|ultraje p\u00fablico ao pudor}}, {{IPA-pt|uw\u02c8t\u027ea\u0292i \u02c8publikw aw pu\u02c8do\u0281|pron}}).\n\nIt is composed of two articles, Art. 233 \"Obscene Act\", \"to practice an obscene act in a public place, or open or exposed to the public\", punished with arrest of three months to one year or a fine; and Art. 234 \"Obscene Written Piece or Object\", to do, import, export, purchase or have in one's property, to ends of trade, distribution or public display, any written, drawn, painted, stamped or object piece of obscenity, punished with arrest of 6 months to 1 years or a fine.<ref>[http://www.dji.com.br/codigos/1940_dl_002848_cp/cp233a234.htm DJi -233 a 234- DL-002.848-1940 - C\u00f2digo Penal - Ultraje P\u00fablico ao Pudor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918053011/http://www.dji.com.br/codigos/1940_dl_002848_cp/cp233a234.htm |date=2013-09-18 }} Dji.com.br, {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\nIt is often used against people who expose their nude bodies in public environments that were not warranted a license to cater to the demographic interested in such practice (the first such place was the [[Praia do Abric\u00f3]] in Rio de Janeiro, in 1994), even if no sexual action took place, and it may include, for example, the chest area of women. Such a thing took place in [[FEMEN]] protests in S\u00e3o Paulo, in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://direito.folha.uol.com.br/1/category/ato+obsceno/1.html|title=Category:|website=Para Entender Direito|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nPervasive points of criticism to the legislation have included:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pauloqueiroz.net/a-proposito-dos-crimes-de-ultraje-publico-ao-pudor/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-02-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221225924/http://pauloqueiroz.net/a-proposito-dos-crimes-de-ultraje-publico-ao-pudor/ |archive-date=2014-02-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* They do not attack anyone's sexual dignity, instead causing outrage at best, but generally just slight discomfort or embarrassment, that can be easily avoided through not looking to such a scene.\n* The Art. 234 is aside obsolete, unconstitutional, for the 1988 post-military dictatorship Constitution having in its Fifth Chapter: \"[the people] are free to the expression of intellectual, artistic, scientific and communicative activity, independently of censorship and license\", reason to which, instead of making it suffer penal restriction, gives any distribution of media the right to be fully exerted.\n* The flourishing Internet culture of Brazil, where such clearly banned media is freely shared in a public place, as well as its pornographic industry and sex shops.\n\n===Exceptions===\nBrazil has about 35 spaces open or mostly open to the public where it is possible to freely practice nudism, its sole public spaces being 8 beaches. They are not criminalized when the clothes-free area is private and away from a view from the street, or through legislation when the beaches are officiated by a municipal decree, for example. It has hosted the meeting of the International Federation of Naturism in 2008, and there is a growing interest in the practice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vidaeestilo.terra.com.br/turismo/praia/conheca-praias-de-nudismo-e-saiba-como-se-comportar,98b4512006c04410VgnVCM4000009bcceb0aRCRD.html|title=Conhe\u00e7a praias de nudismo e saiba como se comportar|website=Vidaeestilo.terra.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Canada==\nIn Canada, s.173 of the ''Criminal Code''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efc.ca/pages/law/cc/cc.part-v.html|title=PART V -- SEXUAL OFFENCES, PUBLIC MORALS AND DISORDERLY CODUCT|website=Efc.ca|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> prohibits \"indecent acts\". There is no statutory definition in the Code of what constitutes an indecent act (other than that the exposure of the genitals for a sexual purpose to anyone under 16 years of age),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-46/page-80.html#h-59|title=Consolidated federal laws of canada, Criminal Code|first=Legislative Services|last=Branch|website=Laws-lois.justice.gc.ca|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> \nso the decision of what state of undress is \"indecent\", and thereby unlawful, is left to judges to decide. Judges have held, for example, that [[nude sunbathing]] is not indecent.<ref>''R. v. Beaupr\u00e9'', 1971, British Columbia Supreme Court. Held: \"mere nude sunbathing is not of sufficient moral turpitude to support a charge for doing an indecent act.\"</ref> Also, [[streaking]] is similarly not regarded as indecent.<ref>''R v Springer'', 1975, Saskatchewan District Court</ref><ref>''R v Niman'', 1974, Ontario Provincial Court</ref> Section 174 prohibits being \"nude\" in a public place or in public view without \"a lawful excuse\", but defines \"nude\" only as being \"so clad as to offend against public decency or order\". The courts have found that [[nude swimming]] is not offensive under this definition.<ref>''R v Benolkin'', 1977, Saskatchewan Court of the Queen's Bench. It was found that \"this offence is not aimed at conduct such as swimming nude at an isolated beach, even where the accused misjudges the loneliness of the beach\".</ref>\n\n[[Toplessness]] is also not an indecent act under s.173. In 1991, Gwen Jacob was arrested for walking in a street in [[Guelph, Ontario]] while topless. She was acquitted in 1996 by the Ontario Court of Appeal on the basis that the act of being topless is not in itself a sexual act or indecent.<ref name=\"QueenvsJacob\">{{Cite document | url = http://www.canlii.org/en/on/onca/doc/1996/1996canlii1119/1996canlii1119.html | title = Judgment C12668, R. vs. Jacob | date = 1996-12-09 | publisher = Province of Ontario Court of Appeal | accessdate = 2009-02-16 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121121082438/http://www.canlii.org/en/on/onca/doc/1996/1996canlii1119/1996canlii1119.html | archivedate = 2012-11-21 }}</ref> The case has been referred to in subsequent cases for the proposition that the mere act of public nudity is not sexual or indecent or an offense.<ref>[http://www.canlii.org/eliisa/highlight.do?language=en&searchTitle=1996+CanLII+1119+%28ON+CA%29&origin=%2Fen%2Fon%2Fonca%2Fdoc%2F1996%2F1996canlii1119%2F1996canlii1119.html&path=/en/bc/bcsc/doc/2000/2000bcsc902/2000bcsc902.html District of Maple Ridge v. Meyer, 2000 BCSC 902 (CanLII)]. See esp. para [49] and [55].</ref> Since then, the court ruling has been tested and upheld several times.\n\nA Canadian legal advice web site observes, \"Canada has a tangle of confusing and inconsistently-enforced nudity laws. . . . The public nudity section is one of the few areas of the Criminal Code that requires the attorney general\u2019s consent to lay a charge, implying a certain grey area around what constitutes illegal nudity. According to the government\u2019s Public Prosecution Service, the attorney general\u2019s consent is needed for two reasons: to avoid the specific harm that could result from prosecuting an innocent person; and to avoid the general harm resulting from prosecuting a case that isn\u2019t in the public interest.<ref> {{Cite web|url=https://criminal.findlaw.ca/article/is-it-legal-to-be-naked-in-canada/|title=FindLaw Canada {{!}} Is it legal to be naked in Canada?|website=criminal.findlaw.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}} </ref>\n\n==Germany==\nGermany has a long history of allowing mixed sex public nudity in designated areas (e.g., beaches and parks). This was true before WW II, after WW II in both West and East Germany and currently. Some of these areas are where clothing is optional and some are where clothing is forbidden (i.e., mandatory nudity). In non-designated areas, appearing nude in public \"counts as a minor breach of the law. Prosecutions can follow if another citizen is offended, but few ever are.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/naked-germany/index.html|title=Nudity in Germany: Here's the naked truth|website=CNN.com|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==India==\nIn [[India]], different acts such as \"indecent exposure\", \"public indecency\", and so on, that involve exposure of a specific body part (genitals, buttocks, anus, nipples on women), a specific intention or effect (being sexually suggestive, offending or annoying observers) are illegal.\n\nPeople in India have the right to wear any dress they like. The [[Constitution of India]] gives their citizens the right to wear anything as per their comfort.\n\nFemale [[Toplessness]] is common in the beaches, especially in tourist paradises like [[Goa]] and [[Puducherry]] etc.<ref>Web results\nTopless Indian women at beaches in Goa - Goa Forum - TripAdvisor\nhttps://www.tripadvisor.in \u203a ShowTopic-...</ref> Women could also become topless during time of [[breastfeeding in public]] and it is a legal right of every woman in the country. [[Nude beaches]] and [[nude recreation|recreation]] areas are present in some parts of the country that allows nudity, where [[naturists]] gather together. [[Nude sunbathing]] is practised by people in these beaches.<ref>{{Places in India where nudist parties are organised secretly - Deccan Chronicle\nhttps://www.deccanchronicle.com \u203a ...}}</ref><ref>https://edtimes.in \u203a Lifestyle\nList Of Nude Beaches In India! Yes! We Know You Will Read This - ED Times</ref>\n\n==New Zealand==\nIn [[New Zealand]], there is no specific law prohibiting nudity in public places. If a person is nude ''and'' also exhibiting lewd and lascivious, or obscene behaviour, then they may fall foul of obscenity laws.<ref name=freebeaches>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebeaches.org.nz/legal.htm|title=Nudity in Public - Legal Aspects|website=www.freebeaches.org.nz|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Police Offences Act 1908 prescribed imprisonment with hard labor for anyone who \"willfully and obscenely exposes his person in any public place or within the view thereof\". Male offenders could, at the court's discretion, also be sentenced to be whipped.<ref>{{cite act|title=Police Offences Act|url=http://www.enzs.auckland.ac.nz/docs/1908/1908C146.pdf|legislature=New Zealand House of Representatives|date=1908|article=41|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> This was replaced in 1981 by the Summary Offences Act, which abolished the hard labor and whipping and changed the offence to consist of the intentional and obscene exposure of the \"genitals\" rather than the \"person\".<ref>{{cite act|title=Summary Offences Act|url=http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1981/0113/latest/DLM53587.html|legislature=New Zealand House of Representatives|date=1981|article=27|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> As well as excusing exposure of the buttocks or female breast from the offence, the change implies \u2013 since the words \"genitals\" and \"obscenely\" are both specified \u2013 that neither one can be automatically taken to imply the other. Public nudity is generally prosecuted under the offensive behaviour or disorderly conduct provisions instead.\n\nThe [[High Court of New Zealand]] has upheld a conviction of disorderly conduct for nudity in the street, because it was not a place where nudity was known to occur or commonplace. Being nude in the street is likely to incur a small fine if a complaint is made against the person, or if the person ignores a police order to cover themselves. However in practice, the likelihood of being prosecuted for nudity on a public ''beach'' is low, and in the past authorities have declined to prosecute topless and nude people on beaches.<ref name=freebeaches/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/editors-picks/6321828/Nudity-not-necessarily-an-offence|title=Nudity not necessarily an offence|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11824550|title=Battle for the beach: Nudists clash with Papamoa beachgoers|date=2017-03-25|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2019-01-11|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 a High Court judge quashed a conviction of offensive behaviour for nudity on a beach in the presence of children, on the grounds that, since the beach in question was \"a place where it was not uncommon for persons to sunbathe in the nude\", a reasonable person would \"regard the conduct... as inappropriate, unnecessary, and in bad taste, but not arousing feelings of anger, disgust, or outrage.\"<ref name=\"ceramalusvpolice\">{{cite court|litigants=Ceramalus v Police|reporter=AP No 76/91|court=[[High Court of New Zealand]]|date=1991-07-05}}</ref> New Zealand is a [[common law]] country, which means that judicial decisions determine the law that subsequent cases must follow.\n\n{{See also|Naturism in New Zealand#Legality}}\n\n==Qatar==\nIn [[Qatar]], the penal code punishes and forbids the wearing of revealing or indecent clothes,<ref name=Doha>{{cite news|title=Organizers are calling this campaign \"One of Us\" - not \"No Nudity\"|url=http://dohanews.co/post/24459500266/update-organizers-are-calling-this-campaign-one|accessdate=7 June 2012|newspaper=Doha News}}</ref> this dressing-code law is enforced by a government body called \"Al-Adheed\". In 2012, a Qatari [[NGO]] organized a campaign of \"public decency\" after they deemed the government to be too lax in monitoring the wearing of revealing clothes; defining the latter as \"not covering shoulders and knees, tight or transparent clothes\".<ref name=Doha/> The campaign targets foreigners who constitute the majority of Qatar's population.<ref name=Doha/>\n\n==Singapore==\nIn [[Singapore]], nudity is illegal. Offenders will be charged under Miscellaneous Offences (Public Order and Nuisance) Act.\n\n==South Africa==\nIn [[South Africa]] specific clothing laws exist for the general public. Nudity is treated under indecent exposure. On 3 April 2015 the country's first official clothing optional beach, Mpenjati Beach near Trafalgar in [[KwaZulu-Natal]], opened after the [[Hibiscus Coast Local Municipality]] approved the South African Nudist Association's (SANNA) application. Although nudity has gradually been tolerated on [[Sandy Bay, Cape Town|Sandy Bay]] in [[Cape Town]] after the National Party (NP) lost the election in 1994, and strict enforcement of its moral values is no longer applied, it is not an official legally recognised public nude beach. Partial nudity is also tolerated on other beaches.\n\n==United Arab Emirates==\nSince 2008, the municipality of [[Dubai]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]] has ensured that signs are posted on beaches warning women against topless bathing and indecent exposure contrary to the cultural values of the UAE. There is no fine for breaking this rule, however a warning is issued and if necessary, ejection from the beach. This was said to be in response to residents' complaints about tourists sunbathing topless or nude and changing their clothes in public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/dubai-takes-action-on-indecent-sunbathing|title=Dubai takes action on 'indecent' sunbathing|website=Thenational.ae|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere are also signs at malls and shopping centers that advocates modest clothing which indicates that shoulders and knees must be covered, and public nudity is against the law. Violation of the law lead to a warning to cease and desist at first and would be followed with arrest if the person chooses to disobey the law.\n\n==United Kingdom==\nThere are three legal jurisdictions in the [[United Kingdom]] ([[England and Wales]], [[Scotland]], and [[Northern Ireland]]). There are a further three jurisdictions that are [[Crown dependencies]] ([[Isle of Man]], [[Bailiwick of Guernsey]] and [[Bailiwick of Jersey]]). The details of the law regarding [[public nudity]] differ substantially between them. In general nudity is not an explicit offence but there are various offences that may apply to nudity in unsuitable circumstances. What constitutes unsuitable circumstances varies according to the jurisdiction but nudity is legal in a much wider range of circumstances than many people assume.\n\nThe [[Crown Prosecution Service]] has published guidance for England and Wales.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cps.gov.uk/legal/l_to_o/nudity_in_public/|title=Nudity in Public - Guidance on handling cases of Naturism|publisher=Crown Prosecution Service|website=Crown Prosecution Service|access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref>, as have the [[College of Policing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.college.police.uk/docs/nudity.pdf|title=Briefing note - Public nudity advice and decision aid|publisher=College of Policing|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[British Naturism]] has published guidance for England and Wales, and Scotland. They are preparing guidance for Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bn.org.uk/activities/frn_legal/|title=Free Range Naturism - Legal Guidance|publisher=British Naturism|website=British Naturism|access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn England and Wales the two statutes most likely to be applicable are s.5 [[Public Order Act 1986]], and for aggressive nudity s.66 [[Sexual Offences Act 2003]].\n\nSee also:\n* [[British Naturism]]\n* [[World Naked Bike Ride]]\n* Great British Skinny Dip\n* [[Stephen Gough]], who became known as the [[Naked Rambler]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/mar/23/naked-rambler-prison|title=The Naked Rambler: the man prepared to go to prison for nudity|first=Neil|last=Forsyth|date=23 March 2012|accessdate=1 November 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\nIn the [[United States]] there are variety of different offenses, such as \"indecent exposure\", \"public lewdness\", \"public indecency\", \"disorderly conduct\" and so on, may involve exposure of a specific body part (genitals, buttocks, anus, nipples on women), a specific intention or effect (being sexually suggestive, offending or annoying observers).  In some cases, a member of the opposite sex must be present.  In Florida, designated nudity areas are given an explicit exception.  There are also some specific prohibitions against sexual acts, such as having [[sexual intercourse in public]], or publicly [[caressing]] someone in a sexual way.  In Indiana and Tennessee, there are specific prohibitions against showing a noticeably [[erection|erect]] penis through clothing, or other sensitive areas through semi-transparent clothing.  In some states, indecent conduct can also occur on private property, depending on the intent or effect of the act.  In some cases there are exceptions for spouses, breastfeeding, and in New York, theatre performances. In most states, there is a governing state statute which defines the offense; in Maryland and Massachusetts, indecency is defined by [[case law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nudistlaw.com/state_laws.htm|title=Naturist State Laws|website=Nudistlaw.com|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>  Some local (county and municipal) governments also regulate personal exposure, as well as commercial activities such as [[strip club]]s.\n\nCase law in general governs the interpretation of the statutory definition, and in some cases allows for additional exceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturisteducation.org/Toni_Egbert_Library/US_District_Courts/us_district_courts.html|title=US District Courts|first=Robert|last=Morton|website=Naturisteducation.org|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nudistlaw.com/Court%20Cases.htm#List%20of%20Cases|title=Nudist Court Cases<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Nudistlaw.com|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn general, exposure of the head, upper chest, and limbs is legal, and considered socially acceptable except among certain religious communities.\n\nFederal, state, and local regulations for certain occupations require various pieces of protective clothing for the safety of the wearer.  Such items include [[hard hat]]s, safety [[vest]]s, life jackets, [[apron]]s, [[hairnet]]s, and [[steel-toe boots]].\n\nIn the first decade of the twenty-first century there was some controversy in some southern U.S. states over the wearing of  trousers so low as to expose the underwear ([[sagging (fashion)|sagging]]). The practice was banned in some places.\n\nSome states and towns have loose, or no, regulations for requiring clothing. The city of San Francisco has a history of [[Social nudity in San Francisco|public nudity]], including at public events such as [[Bay to Breakers]]. The town of [[Brattleboro, Vermont|Brattleboro]], [[Vermont|VT]], experienced a brief period during which there was public nudity, until a law was passed banning it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brattleborochamber.org/one-and-only|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315061920/http://brattleborochamber.org/one-and-only|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 March 2013|title=The One and Only - Brattleboro Vermont|date=15 March 2013|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Summary of various countries ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Country\n! scope=\"col\" | Attire laws\n! scope=\"col\" | Maximum penalty\n|-\n|France\n|Chest and private parts must be covered except near bathing zones. [[Burqa]] banned.\n|article 222-32: \"Publicly visible sexual exhibition in public zones\" punishable by 1 year of imprisonment and 15,000 fine.\n|-\n|Germany\n|There are no explicit legal regulations on clothing in Germany. Nudity on private grounds is considered as legal even if visible from outside. The same applies for naked sunbathing as long as not otherwise stated by local laws. On the other hand, naked jogging or naked cycling have been considered in certain circumstances as public nuisance by several courts.<br>\nNote: The German Penal Code determines \"exhibitionism\" (sec. 183) as an act of public exposure committed by a man for sexual arrousal and \"causing a public disturbance\" (sec. 183a) as a sexual activity in public. Therefore, non-sexual nudity is not considered as crime or misdemeanour.\n|Section 118 of the Act on Regulatory Offences: \"(1) Whoever commits a grossly offensive act which is apt to disturb or endanger the public and to prejudice public order shall be deemed to have committed a regulatory offence.<br>\n(2) The regulatory offence may be sanctioned by a regulatory fine unless the act may be sanctioned pursuant to other provisions.\"<br>\nThe regulatory fine is between 5 and 1.000 Euros (sec. 17 (2) of the act). More likely, the local or state police may politely demand to cover up without further sanction or a cautionary fine of 5 to 55 Euros if immediately obeyed (sec. 56 (1) of the act).\n|-\n|Netherlands\n|Nude recreation in the Netherlands has been described in article 430a of the criminal law. The city council can designate public places found suitable for nude recreation. Nude recreation in such places is always allowed. This does however not mean it is forbidden everywhere outside these designated places. It is only disallowed in places accessible to the general public found unsuitable for nude recreation. Whether a place is suitable or not is decided by the judge, not by the government. There have been a number of law cases about this, so jurisprudence is available. In general most places have been found suitable.\n|A fine of the first category (maximum \u20ac 410,-).\n|-\n|Spain\n|Spanish law does not have any article that prohibits public nudity, it is therefore always allowed. Regional laws have changed and Barcelona for example has banned nudity or semi-nudity on the streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.catalannews.com/society-science/item/barcelona-city-council-bans-nudity-and-semi-nudity-on-the-streets|title=Barcelona City Council bans nudity and semi-nudity on the streets|last=Garrido|first=CNA / Rafa|website=www.catalannews.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n|Regional penalty possible.  Barcelona from 120 euros to 500 euros. Note regional changes.\n|-\n|Sudan\n|Females must wear dresses, and socks. \n|\"indecent or immoral dress\" punishable by 40 lashes, a fine, or both.\n|-\n|Qatar\n|Clothes must cover shoulders and be lower than knees. Soles of feet or shoes should not be shown. No public affection.\n|Unspecified reprimand.\n|-\n|US\n|State laws vary, from no proactive ban on nudity, to bans on breastfeeding. Indecent exposure and lewd conduct is illegal and its definition is based on case law.\n|Someone convicted of felony indecent exposure can be punished with: Incarceration, fines, probation, community service. Sexual offender registry in some states. \n|}\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dress code]]\n* [[Hijab by country]]\n* [[Trousers#Laws]]\n* [[Sumptuary law]]\n* [[Jewish hat]]\n* [[Zunnar]]\n* [[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)]]\n* ''[[Let's trim our hair in accordance with the socialist lifestyle]]'' (North Korea)\n* [[Islamic dress in Europe]]\n* [[Beard and haircut laws by country]]\n**[[Beard tax]]\n*[[Emo killings in Iraq]]\n*[[Modesty police]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{nudity}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Clothing by country]]\n[[Category:Clothing controversies]]\n[[Category:Nudity]]\n[[Category:Naturism]]\n[[Category:Law by country|Clothing]]\n[[Category:Modesty]]\n[[Category:Dress codes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=June 2008}}\n\n[[File:Poster of a public decency campaign in Qatar.png|thumb|200px|right|Poster in Qatar calling on foreign women to dress modestly]]\n[[Clothing]] laws vary considerably around the world. In general, in most countries, there are no laws which prescribe what clothing is required to be worn. However, the community standards of clothing are set indirectly by way of prosecution of those who wear something that is not socially approved. Those people who wear insufficient clothing can be prosecuted in many countries under various offences termed [[indecent exposure]], public indecency or other descriptions. Generally, these offences do not themselves define what is and what is not acceptable clothing to constitute the offence, and leave it to a judge to determine in each case.\n\nMost clothing laws concern which parts of the body must ''not'' be exposed to view; there are exceptions. Some countries have strict clothing laws, such as in some [[Islamic]] countries. Other countries are more tolerant of non-conventional attire and are relaxed about nudity.  Many countries have different laws and customs for men and women, what may be allowed or perceived often varies by gender.<ref Name=\"Kirby\">{{cite book\n  | last =Kirby\n  | first =Kathleen M. \n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title =Indifferent boundaries: spatial concepts of human subjectivity\n  | publisher =Guilford Press\n  | year =1996\n  | location =\n  | url =https://books.google.com/?id=Y4PcShmKe-YC&pg=PA132&dq=different+laws+for+men+and+women,+public+nudity+is+legal+on+most+beaches#PPA124,M1\n  | doi =\n  | isbn = 0-89862-572-6\n\n  | page = Chapter 5 }}</ref>\n\nSeparate laws are usually in place to regulate [[obscenity]], which includes certain depictions of people in various states of undress, and [[child pornography]], which may include similar photographs of children.\n\nIn some countries, non-sexual toplessness or nudity is legal. However, private or public establishments can establish a [[dress code]] which requires visitors to wear prescribed clothing.\n\nThere are a variety of laws around the world which affect what people can and cannot wear. For example, some laws require a person in authority to wear the appropriate uniform. For example, a police officer on duty may be required to wear a uniform; and it can be illegal for the general public to wear a police officer's uniform. The same could apply to firefighters and other emergency personnel. In some countries, for example in Australia, the [[Scouts Australia|boy scouts]] uniform is also protected.\n\nIn most [[Court|courts of law]], lawyers and judges are required by law or custom to wear [[Court Dress|court dress]], which may entail robes or traditional wigs.\n\nIn many countries, regulations require workers to wear protective clothing, such as [[safety helmet]]s, shoes, vests, etc., as appropriate. The obligation is generally on employers to ensure that their workers wear the appropriate protective clothing. Similarly, health regulations may require those who handle food to wear hair covering, gloves and other clothing.\n\nGovernments can also influence standards of dress shown on television through its licensing powers.\n\nIn addition to nude beaches and similar exceptional locations, there are some public events in which nudity is tolerated more than usual, such as the [[naked bike ride]]s held in several countries.\n\n== International laws and customs and culture ==\nThere are many specific circumstances where body parts have to be covered, often for safety or sanitary reasons.\n\nIn Saudi Arabia and Iran, women must conceal almost their entire bodies (see [[hijab]]).\n\n==Australia==\n\nIn [[Australia]], [[indecent exposure]] laws only refer to the genital area. However, many local councils impose their own rules, and have the power to ask topless people to leave an area.<ref name=Lifehackerau>{{cite news|title=Is it legal to sunbathe topless in Australia?|date=Nov 30, 2015|access-date= Nov 12, 2018|author=Chris Jager|publisher=Lifehacker|url=https://www.lifehacker.com.au/2015/11/is-it-legal-to-sunbathe-topless/}}</ref> Additionally, women who go topless are sometimes slapped with more vague charges such as being a public nuisance, or offensive behaviour.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=How to Legally #FreeTheNipple in Australia|date=March 11, 2016|access-date= Nov 12, 2018|author=Katherine Gillespie|magazine=Vice.com|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_au/article/mbv4pb/how-to-legally-freethenipple-in-australia}}</ref>\n\nOn public beaches, local bylaws are not heavily enforced, and women can often sunbathe topless without fuss.<ref name=Lifehackerau></ref>\n\nBreastfeeding in public places is a legal right in Australia. Under the [[Sex Discrimination Act 1984]], no business or service provider can discriminate against a breastfeeding woman.<ref>{{cite article|url=https://www.breastfeeding.asn.au/bf-info/breastfeeding-and-law/legalright|title=Breastfeeding in public - your legal rights|date=Aug 2016|access-date=12 Nov 2018|publisher=Australian Breastfeeding Association}}</ref>\n\n==Brazil==\nEver since 1940, in the Title VI of the Penal Code, naming crimes against sexual dignity (until 2009 crimes against [social] conventions), the fourth chapter is dedicated to a crime named \"public outrage [related] to modesty\" ({{lang-pt|ultraje p\u00fablico ao pudor}}, {{IPA-pt|uw\u02c8t\u027ea\u0292i \u02c8publikw aw pu\u02c8do\u0281|pron}}).\n\nIt is composed of two articles, Art. 233 \"Obscene Act\", \"to practice an obscene act in a public place, or open or exposed to the public\", punished with arrest of 3 months to 1 year or a fine; and Art. 234 \"Obscene Written Piece or Object\", to do, import, export, purchase or have in one's property, to ends of trade, distribution or public display, any written, drawn, painted, stamped or object piece of obscenity, punished with arrest of 6 months to 1 years or a fine.<ref>[http://www.dji.com.br/codigos/1940_dl_002848_cp/cp233a234.htm DJi -233 a 234- DL-002.848-1940 - C\u00f2digo Penal - Ultraje P\u00fablico ao Pudor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918053011/http://www.dji.com.br/codigos/1940_dl_002848_cp/cp233a234.htm |date=2013-09-18 }} Dji.com.br, {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\nIt is often used against people who expose their nude bodies in public environments that were not warranted a license to cater to the demographic interested in such practice (the first such place was the [[Praia do Abric\u00f3]] in Rio de Janeiro, in 1994), even if no sexual action took place, and it may include, for example, the chest area of women. Such a thing took place in [[FEMEN]] protests in S\u00e3o Paulo, in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://direito.folha.uol.com.br/1/category/ato+obsceno/1.html|title=Category:|website=Para Entender Direito|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nPervasive points of criticism to the legislation have included:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pauloqueiroz.net/a-proposito-dos-crimes-de-ultraje-publico-ao-pudor/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-02-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221225924/http://pauloqueiroz.net/a-proposito-dos-crimes-de-ultraje-publico-ao-pudor/ |archive-date=2014-02-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* They do not attack anyone's sexual dignity, instead causing outrage at best, but generally just slight discomfort or embarrassment, that can be easily avoided through not looking to such a scene.\n* The Art. 234 is aside obsolete, unconstitutional, for the 1988 post-military dictatorship Constitution having in its Fifth Chapter: \"[the people] are free to the expression of intellectual, artistic, scientific and communicative activity, independently of censorship and license\", reason to which, instead of making it suffer penal restriction, gives any distribution of media the right to be fully exerted.\n* The flourishing Internet culture of Brazil, where such clearly banned media is freely shared in a public place, as well as its pornographic industry and sex shops.\n\n===Exceptions===\nBrazil has about 35 spaces open or mostly open to the public where it is possible to freely practice nudism, its sole public spaces being 8 beaches. They are not criminalized when the clothes-free area is private and away from a view from the street, or through legislation when the beaches are officiated by a municipal decree, for example. It has hosted the meeting of the International Federation of Naturism in 2008, and there is a growing interest in the practice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vidaeestilo.terra.com.br/turismo/praia/conheca-praias-de-nudismo-e-saiba-como-se-comportar,98b4512006c04410VgnVCM4000009bcceb0aRCRD.html|title=Conhe\u00e7a praias de nudismo e saiba como se comportar|website=Vidaeestilo.terra.com.br|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Canada==\nIn Canada, s.173 of the ''Criminal Code''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efc.ca/pages/law/cc/cc.part-v.html|title=PART V -- SEXUAL OFFENCES, PUBLIC MORALS AND DISORDERLY CODUCT|website=Efc.ca|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> prohibits \"indecent acts\". There is no statutory definition in the Code of what constitutes an indecent act (other than that the exposure of the genitals for a sexual purpose to anyone under 16 years of age),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-46/page-80.html#h-59|title=Consolidated federal laws of canada, Criminal Code|first=Legislative Services|last=Branch|website=Laws-lois.justice.gc.ca|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> \nso the decision of what state of undress is \"indecent\", and thereby unlawful, is left to judges to decide. Judges have held, for example, that [[nude sunbathing]] is not indecent.<ref>''R. v. Beaupr\u00e9'', 1971, British Columbia Supreme Court. Held: \"mere nude sunbathing is not of sufficient moral turpitude to support a charge for doing an indecent act.\"</ref> Also, [[streaking]] is similarly not regarded as indecent.<ref>''R v Springer'', 1975, Saskatchewan District Court</ref><ref>''R v Niman'', 1974, Ontario Provincial Court</ref> Section 174 prohibits being \"nude\" in a public place or in public view without \"a lawful excuse\", but defines \"nude\" only as being \"so clad as to offend against public decency or order\". The courts have found that [[nude swimming]] is not offensive under this definition.<ref>''R v Benolkin'', 1977, Saskatchewan Court of the Queen's Bench. It was found that \"this offence is not aimed at conduct such as swimming nude at an isolated beach, even where the accused misjudges the loneliness of the beach\".</ref>\n\n[[Toplessness]] is also not an indecent act under s.173. In 1991, Gwen Jacob was arrested for walking in a street in [[Guelph, Ontario]] while topless. She was acquitted in 1996 by the Ontario Court of Appeal on the basis that the act of being topless is not in itself a sexual act or indecent.<ref name=\"QueenvsJacob\">{{Cite document | url = http://www.canlii.org/en/on/onca/doc/1996/1996canlii1119/1996canlii1119.html | title = Judgment C12668, R. vs. Jacob | date = 1996-12-09 | publisher = Province of Ontario Court of Appeal | accessdate = 2009-02-16 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121121082438/http://www.canlii.org/en/on/onca/doc/1996/1996canlii1119/1996canlii1119.html | archivedate = 2012-11-21 }}</ref> The case has been referred to in subsequent cases for the proposition that the mere act of public nudity is not sexual or indecent or an offense.<ref>[http://www.canlii.org/eliisa/highlight.do?language=en&searchTitle=1996+CanLII+1119+%28ON+CA%29&origin=%2Fen%2Fon%2Fonca%2Fdoc%2F1996%2F1996canlii1119%2F1996canlii1119.html&path=/en/bc/bcsc/doc/2000/2000bcsc902/2000bcsc902.html District of Maple Ridge v. Meyer, 2000 BCSC 902 (CanLII)]. See esp. para [49] and [55].</ref> Since then, the court ruling has been tested and upheld several times.\n\nA Canadian legal advice web site observes, \"Canada has a tangle of confusing and inconsistently-enforced nudity laws. . . . The public nudity section is one of the few areas of the Criminal Code that requires the attorney general\u2019s consent to lay a charge, implying a certain grey area around what constitutes illegal nudity. According to the government\u2019s Public Prosecution Service, the attorney general\u2019s consent is needed for two reasons: to avoid the specific harm that could result from prosecuting an innocent person; and to avoid the general harm resulting from prosecuting a case that isn\u2019t in the public interest.<ref> {{Cite web|url=https://criminal.findlaw.ca/article/is-it-legal-to-be-naked-in-canada/|title=FindLaw Canada {{!}} Is it legal to be naked in Canada?|website=criminal.findlaw.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}} </ref>\n\n==Germany==\nGermany has a long history of allowing mixed sex public nudity in designated areas (e.g., beaches and parks). This was true before WW II, after WW II in both West and East Germany and currently. Some of these areas are where clothing is optional and some are where clothing is forbidden (i.e., mandatory nudity). In non-designated areas, appearing nude in public \"counts as a minor breach of the law. Prosecutions can follow if another citizen is offended, but few ever are.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/naked-germany/index.html|title=Nudity in Germany: Here's the naked truth|website=CNN.com|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==India==\nIn [[India]], different acts such as \"indecent exposure\", \"public indecency\", and so on, that involve exposure of a specific body part (genitals, buttocks, anus, nipples on women), a specific intention or effect (being sexually suggestive, offending or annoying observers) are illegal.\n\nPeople in India have the right to wear any dress they like. The [[Constitution of India]] gives their citizens the right to wear anything as per their comfort.\n\nFemale [[Toplessness]] is common in the beaches, especially in tourist paradises like [[Goa]] and [[Puducherry]] etc.<ref>Web results\nTopless Indian women at beaches in Goa - Goa Forum - TripAdvisor\nhttps://www.tripadvisor.in \u203a ShowTopic-...</ref> Women could also become topless during time of [[breastfeeding in public]] and it is a legal right of every woman in the country. [[Nude beaches]] and [[nude recreation|recreation]] areas are present in some parts of the country that allows nudity, where [[naturists]] gather together. [[Nude sunbathing]] is practised by people in these beaches.<ref>{{Places in India where nudist parties are organised secretly - Deccan Chronicle\nhttps://www.deccanchronicle.com \u203a ...}}</ref><ref>https://edtimes.in \u203a Lifestyle\nList Of Nude Beaches In India! Yes! We Know You Will Read This - ED Times</ref>\n\n==New Zealand==\nIn [[New Zealand]], there is no specific law prohibiting nudity in public places. If a person is nude ''and'' also exhibiting lewd and lascivious, or obscene behaviour, then they may fall foul of obscenity laws.<ref name=freebeaches>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freebeaches.org.nz/legal.htm|title=Nudity in Public - Legal Aspects|website=www.freebeaches.org.nz|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Police Offences Act 1908 prescribed imprisonment with hard labor for anyone who \"willfully and obscenely exposes his person in any public place or within the view thereof\". Male offenders could, at the court's discretion, also be sentenced to be whipped.<ref>{{cite act|title=Police Offences Act|url=http://www.enzs.auckland.ac.nz/docs/1908/1908C146.pdf|legislature=New Zealand House of Representatives|date=1908|article=41|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> This was replaced in 1981 by the Summary Offences Act, which abolished the hard labor and whipping and changed the offence to consist of the intentional and obscene exposure of the \"genitals\" rather than the \"person\".<ref>{{cite act|title=Summary Offences Act|url=http://www.legislation.govt.nz/act/public/1981/0113/latest/DLM53587.html|legislature=New Zealand House of Representatives|date=1981|article=27|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> As well as excusing exposure of the buttocks or female breast from the offence, the change implies \u2013 since the words \"genitals\" and \"obscenely\" are both specified \u2013 that neither one can be automatically taken to imply the other. Public nudity is generally prosecuted under the offensive behaviour or disorderly conduct provisions instead.\n\nThe [[High Court of New Zealand]] has upheld a conviction of disorderly conduct for nudity in the street, because it was not a place where nudity was known to occur or commonplace. Being nude in the street is likely to incur a small fine if a complaint is made against the person, or if the person ignores a police order to cover themselves. However in practice, the likelihood of being prosecuted for nudity on a public ''beach'' is low, and in the past authorities have declined to prosecute topless and nude people on beaches.<ref name=freebeaches/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/editors-picks/6321828/Nudity-not-necessarily-an-offence|title=Nudity not necessarily an offence|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11824550|title=Battle for the beach: Nudists clash with Papamoa beachgoers|date=2017-03-25|work=NZ Herald|access-date=2019-01-11|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991 a High Court judge quashed a conviction of offensive behaviour for nudity on a beach in the presence of children, on the grounds that, since the beach in question was \"a place where it was not uncommon for persons to sunbathe in the nude\", a reasonable person would \"regard the conduct... as inappropriate, unnecessary, and in bad taste, but not arousing feelings of anger, disgust, or outrage.\"<ref name=\"ceramalusvpolice\">{{cite court|litigants=Ceramalus v Police|reporter=AP No 76/91|court=[[High Court of New Zealand]]|date=1991-07-05}}</ref> New Zealand is a [[common law]] country, which means that judicial decisions determine the law that subsequent cases must follow.\n\n{{See also|Naturism in New Zealand#Legality}}\n\n==Qatar==\nIn [[Qatar]], the penal code punishes and forbids the wearing of revealing or indecent clothes,<ref name=Doha>{{cite news|title=Organizers are calling this campaign \"One of Us\" - not \"No Nudity\"|url=http://dohanews.co/post/24459500266/update-organizers-are-calling-this-campaign-one|accessdate=7 June 2012|newspaper=Doha News}}</ref> this dressing-code law is enforced by a government body called \"Al-Adheed\". In 2012, a Qatari [[NGO]] organized a campaign of \"public decency\" after they deemed the government to be too lax in monitoring the wearing of revealing clothes; defining the latter as \"not covering shoulders and knees, tight or transparent clothes\".<ref name=Doha/> The campaign targets foreigners who constitute the majority of Qatar's population.<ref name=Doha/>\n\n==Singapore==\nIn [[Singapore]], nudity is illegal. Offenders will be charged under Miscellaneous Offences (Public Order and Nuisance) Act.\n\n==South Africa==\nIn [[South Africa]] specific clothing laws exist for the general public. Nudity is treated under indecent exposure. On 3 April 2015 the country's first official clothing optional beach, Mpenjati Beach near Trafalgar in [[KwaZulu-Natal]], opened after the [[Hibiscus Coast Local Municipality]] approved the South African Nudist Association's (SANNA) application. Although nudity has gradually been tolerated on [[Sandy Bay, Cape Town|Sandy Bay]] in [[Cape Town]] after the National Party (NP) lost the election in 1994, and strict enforcement of its moral values is no longer applied, it is not an official legally recognised public nude beach. Partial nudity is also tolerated on other beaches.\n\n==United Arab Emirates==\nSince 2008, the municipality of [[Dubai]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]] has ensured that signs are posted on beaches warning women against topless bathing and indecent exposure contrary to the cultural values of the UAE. There is no fine for breaking this rule, however a warning is issued and if necessary, ejection from the beach. This was said to be in response to residents' complaints about tourists sunbathing topless or nude and changing their clothes in public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/dubai-takes-action-on-indecent-sunbathing|title=Dubai takes action on 'indecent' sunbathing|website=Thenational.ae|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere are also signs at malls and shopping centers that advocates modest clothing which indicates that shoulders and knees must be covered, and public nudity is against the law. Violation of the law lead to a warning to cease and desist at first and would be followed with arrest if the person chooses to disobey the law.\n\n==United Kingdom==\nThere are three legal jurisdictions in the [[United Kingdom]] ([[England and Wales]], [[Scotland]], and [[Northern Ireland]]). There are a further three jurisdictions that are [[Crown dependencies]] ([[Isle of Man]], [[Bailiwick of Guernsey]] and [[Bailiwick of Jersey]]). The details of the law regarding [[public nudity]] differ substantially between them. In general nudity is not an explicit offence but there are various offences that may apply to nudity in unsuitable circumstances. What constitutes unsuitable circumstances varies according to the jurisdiction but nudity is legal in a much wider range of circumstances than many people assume.\n\nThe [[Crown Prosecution Service]] has published guidance for England and Wales.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cps.gov.uk/legal/l_to_o/nudity_in_public/|title=Nudity in Public - Guidance on handling cases of Naturism|publisher=Crown Prosecution Service|website=Crown Prosecution Service|access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref>, as have the [[College of Policing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.college.police.uk/docs/nudity.pdf|title=Briefing note - Public nudity advice and decision aid|publisher=College of Policing|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[British Naturism]] has published guidance for England and Wales, and Scotland. They are preparing guidance for Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bn.org.uk/activities/frn_legal/|title=Free Range Naturism - Legal Guidance|publisher=British Naturism|website=British Naturism|access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn England and Wales the two statutes most likely to be applicable are s.5 [[Public Order Act 1986]], and for aggressive nudity s.66 [[Sexual Offences Act 2003]].\n\nSee also:\n* [[British Naturism]]\n* [[World Naked Bike Ride]]\n* Great British Skinny Dip\n* [[Stephen Gough]], who became known as the [[Naked Rambler]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/mar/23/naked-rambler-prison|title=The Naked Rambler: the man prepared to go to prison for nudity|first=Neil|last=Forsyth|date=23 March 2012|accessdate=1 November 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\nIn the [[United States]] there are variety of different offenses, such as \"indecent exposure\", \"public lewdness\", \"public indecency\", \"disorderly conduct\" and so on, may involve exposure of a specific body part (genitals, buttocks, anus, nipples on women), a specific intention or effect (being sexually suggestive, offending or annoying observers).  In some cases, a member of the opposite sex must be present.  In Florida, designated nudity areas are given an explicit exception.  There are also some specific prohibitions against sexual acts, such as having [[sexual intercourse in public]], or publicly [[caressing]] someone in a sexual way.  In Indiana and Tennessee, there are specific prohibitions against showing a noticeably [[erection|erect]] penis through clothing, or other sensitive areas through semi-transparent clothing.  In some states, indecent conduct can also occur on private property, depending on the intent or effect of the act.  In some cases there are exceptions for spouses, breastfeeding, and in New York, theatre performances. In most states, there is a governing state statute which defines the offense; in Maryland and Massachusetts, indecency is defined by [[case law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nudistlaw.com/state_laws.htm|title=Naturist State Laws|website=Nudistlaw.com|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>  Some local (county and municipal) governments also regulate personal exposure, as well as commercial activities such as [[strip club]]s.\n\nCase law in general governs the interpretation of the statutory definition, and in some cases allows for additional exceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturisteducation.org/Toni_Egbert_Library/US_District_Courts/us_district_courts.html|title=US District Courts|first=Robert|last=Morton|website=Naturisteducation.org|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nudistlaw.com/Court%20Cases.htm#List%20of%20Cases|title=Nudist Court Cases<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Nudistlaw.com|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn general, exposure of the head, upper chest, and limbs is legal, and considered socially acceptable except among certain religious communities.\n\nFederal, state, and local regulations for certain occupations require various pieces of protective clothing for the safety of the wearer.  Such items include [[hard hat]]s, safety [[vest]]s, life jackets, [[apron]]s, [[hairnet]]s, and [[steel-toe boots]].\n\nIn the first decade of the twenty-first century there was some controversy in some southern U.S. states over the wearing of  trousers so low as to expose the underwear ([[sagging (fashion)|sagging]]). The practice was banned in some places.\n\nSome states and towns have loose, or no, regulations for requiring clothing. The city of San Francisco has a history of [[Social nudity in San Francisco|public nudity]], including at public events such as [[Bay to Breakers]]. The town of [[Brattleboro, Vermont|Brattleboro]], [[Vermont|VT]], experienced a brief period during which there was public nudity, until a law was passed banning it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brattleborochamber.org/one-and-only|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315061920/http://brattleborochamber.org/one-and-only|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 March 2013|title=The One and Only - Brattleboro Vermont|date=15 March 2013|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Summary of various countries ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Country\n! scope=\"col\" | Attire laws\n! scope=\"col\" | Maximum penalty\n|-\n|France\n|Chest and private parts must be covered except near bathing zones. [[Burqa]] banned.\n|article 222-32: \"Publicly visible sexual exhibition in public zones\" punishable by 1 year of imprisonment and 15,000 fine.\n|-\n|Germany\n|There are no explicit legal regulations on clothing in Germany. Nudity on private grounds is considered as legal even if visible from outside. The same applies for naked sunbathing as long as not otherwise stated by local laws. On the other hand, naked jogging or naked cycling have been considered in certain circumstances as public nuisance by several courts.<br>\nNote: The German Penal Code determines \"exhibitionism\" (sec. 183) as an act of public exposure committed by a man for sexual arrousal and \"causing a public disturbance\" (sec. 183a) as a sexual activity in public. Therefore, non-sexual nudity is not considered as crime or misdemeanour.\n|Section 118 of the Act on Regulatory Offences: \"(1) Whoever commits a grossly offensive act which is apt to disturb or endanger the public and to prejudice public order shall be deemed to have committed a regulatory offence.<br>\n(2) The regulatory offence may be sanctioned by a regulatory fine unless the act may be sanctioned pursuant to other provisions.\"<br>\nThe regulatory fine is between 5 and 1.000 Euros (sec. 17 (2) of the act). More likely, the local or state police may politely demand to cover up without further sanction or a cautionary fine of 5 to 55 Euros if immediately obeyed (sec. 56 (1) of the act).\n|-\n|Netherlands\n|Nude recreation in the Netherlands has been described in article 430a of the criminal law. The city council can designate public places found suitable for nude recreation. Nude recreation in such places is always allowed. This does however not mean it is forbidden everywhere outside these designated places. It is only disallowed in places accessible to the general public found unsuitable for nude recreation. Whether a place is suitable or not is decided by the judge, not by the government. There have been a number of law cases about this, so jurisprudence is available. In general most places have been found suitable.\n|A fine of the first category (maximum \u20ac 410,-).\n|-\n|Spain\n|Spanish law does not have any article that prohibits public nudity, it is therefore always allowed. Regional laws have changed and Barcelona for example has banned nudity or semi-nudity on the streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.catalannews.com/society-science/item/barcelona-city-council-bans-nudity-and-semi-nudity-on-the-streets|title=Barcelona City Council bans nudity and semi-nudity on the streets|last=Garrido|first=CNA / Rafa|website=www.catalannews.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n|Regional penalty possible.  Barcelona from 120 euros to 500 euros. Note regional changes.\n|-\n|Sudan\n|Females must wear dresses, and socks. \n|\"indecent or immoral dress\" punishable by 40 lashes, a fine, or both.\n|-\n|Qatar\n|Clothes must cover shoulders and be lower than knees. Soles of feet or shoes should not be shown. No public affection.\n|Unspecified reprimand.\n|-\n|US\n|State laws vary, from no proactive ban on nudity, to bans on breastfeeding. Indecent exposure and lewd conduct is illegal and its definition is based on case law.\n|Someone convicted of felony indecent exposure can be punished with: Incarceration, fines, probation, community service. Sexual offender registry in some states. \n|}\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dress code]]\n* [[Hijab by country]]\n* [[Trousers#Laws]]\n* [[Sumptuary law]]\n* [[Jewish hat]]\n* [[Zunnar]]\n* [[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)]]\n* ''[[Let's trim our hair in accordance with the socialist lifestyle]]'' (North Korea)\n* [[Islamic dress in Europe]]\n* [[Beard and haircut laws by country]]\n**[[Beard tax]]\n*[[Emo killings in Iraq]]\n*[[Modesty police]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{nudity}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Clothing by country]]\n[[Category:Clothing controversies]]\n[[Category:Nudity]]\n[[Category:Naturism]]\n[[Category:Law by country|Clothing]]\n[[Category:Modesty]]\n[[Category:Dress codes]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBrazil:spelled out numbers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clothing_laws_by_country"}
{"title_page": "Amrish Ranjan Pandey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder|office=Spokesperson [[Indian Youth Congress]]|\n | name               = Amrish Ranjan Pandey \n| image          =\n|alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Amrish Ranjan Pandey (Age 30)\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = [[Madhubani, Bihar|Madhubani]], [[Bihar]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = [[Politician]]\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Politician]]\n| notable_works      = \n| home_town          = \n| party              = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| website = {{URL |amrishranjanpandey.in}}\n\n}}\n'''Amrish Ranjan Pandey''' is a youth leader and is currently officiating as the National Secretary, National Media Incharge and Chief Spokesperson of the [[Indian Youth Congress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iyc.in/About-Us/national-leadership/P42|title=National Leadership|website=iyc.in|access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> He was appointed the National Secretary of IYC in March, 2020. Along with being an active face in youth politics he is also a practising lawyer in Delhi-NCR region.\n\nHe started his political career with [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]]'s student Wing [[National Students' Union of India|NSUI]].  He has been very active in both student and youth politics at [[Indian Youth Congress|IYC]] and [[National Students' Union of India|NSUI]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/Amrish-Ranjan-Pandey|title=Amrish Ranjan Pandey: Latest News, Videos and Photos of Amrish Ranjan Pandey {{!}} Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/youth-congress-workers-detained-during-protest-over-rafale-deal-118110200837_1.html|title=Youth Congress workers detained during protest over Rafale deal|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2018-11-02|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/iyc-activists-hold-protest-demand-jaitley-s-resignation-over-mehul-choksi-issue-118102301102_1.html|title=IYC activists hold protest, demand Jaitley's resignation over Mehul Choksi issue|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2018-10-23|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-11-16}}proprojects. ject. KAS-CSDS study on Youth in Indian politics. s</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAmrish was born in [[Bihar]] on 25 October 1988, as son of Shri Arun kumar Pandey and Smt. Rajkumari Pandey. He traces his lineage to Shri [[Damodar Pande|Damodar pande]], who was the [[Mulkaji]] of Nepal from 1803 to 1804 and is also popularly known as the first Prime Minister of Nepal. Another significant face from Amrish's family is [[Rana Jang Pande]], who was the third Mukhtiyar or Prime Minister of Nepal. After a political conspiracy, Amrish's forefathers shifted to [[Madhubani, India|Madhubani, Bihar]] and the family has been settled there since. Having completed his primary and secondary education from [[Watson High School, Madhubani|Watson High School]], Madhubani, Amrish has strong ties with Madhubani. \n\n== Education and Leadership Training ==\nIn year 2008, Amrish completed his Bachelor's degree in Philosophy from [[Zakir Husain Delhi College|Zakir Hussain College]], University of Delhi and thereafter completed his master's degree from [[University of Delhi]]. Amrish had his first rendezvous with politics, when he joined [[National Students' Union of India|National Students Union of India]] in 2005, while studying at the Zakir Hussain College and since then he has never looked back. He is [[Bachelor of Law]] from Campus Law Center [[Delhi University]].\n\nAmrish is a political leader, not just by passion but also by formal training. He has been an active participant at various Konrad Adenauer School for Young Politicians Programme (KASYP) established by [[Konrad Adenauer Foundation]]. He was first granted a fellowship by the foundation in 2013. Since then Amrish has attended several KASYP workshops. He was also called on to attend the Legislative Fellow Program by U.S. Department of State in 2016, wherein, Amrish worked with the office of the Speaker, Columbus, [[Ohio|Ohio\ufffc]]. Thereafter, he also attended the Professional Fellows Congress (Office of Citizen Exchanges), Washington D.C. As an alumnus of [[Konrad Adenauer Foundation]], Amrish has represented India in various programs. A detailed list of the same is as follows:\n\n# Workshop on Political Parties Functions and Organisation in Democratic Societies in [[Yangon|Yongon]], Myanmar in Jan/Feb, 2013.\n# International Workshop on Youth and Politics in May, 2013 held in [[Singapore]].\n# Workshop on Local Governance and Development in August, 2013 in Singapore.\n# Workshop on Leadership Training in Campaigning and Advertising organised in the month of March, 2014 in [[Kuala Lumpur]]\ufffc.\n#Workshop on Political Party Organization and local politics in September, 2014 in [[Berlin]] and [[Erfurt]], Germany.\n#Workshop on Political Party Organization and local politics in November, 2015 in [[Davao City|Davao]].\n#KAS Young Political Leaders Caucus Meeting, 2017 for Sustainable Development Goals in [[Siem Reap|SiemReap]], Cambodia in February, 2017.\n#KAS Young Political Leaders Caucus Meeting, 2018 for Sustainable Development Goals in [[Bangkok]] in December, 2018.\n#KASYP grand Alumni meeting in the year 2019 held at [[Penang]], Malaysia.\n# \n\n==Administrative Roles ==\n# Founder and Director - '''The Democratic Mirror''' - A Unique talk show on [[Media (communication)|Media]] and [[Politics]].\n#[[Chairman|President]] - [[Center For Public Initiatives]] ([[NGO]])\n#Former [[Secretary]] - Gandhi Study Circle at [[Zakir Husain Delhi College|Zakir hussain College]]\n#Associate [[Volunteer]] - Gandhi Smriti and Darsan Samiti [[New Delhi]].\n#Amrish is also the host and Director for a weekly talk show titled \"Unveiling Political Truths\", where he hosts renowned political personalities, journalists, educationists, and academicians etc. The show has hosted several personalities so far including [[Punya Prasun Bajpai]], [[Sandeep Dikshit]], [[Vivek Tankha]], [[Rajiv Tyagi]] and [[Jaiveer Shergill]] etc.\n#Amrish and his media team also launched a nationwide oratory competition named Young India Ke Bol.\n#\n#\n#\n#\n\n==Social Contribution==\n'''Major Programmes Organized'''\n\nActed as a volunteer of an International Seminar on Cultural Diversity in South Asia organized by Zakir Husain College in collaboration with Asia Project, India International Cente\n\n==Political career==\nAmrish first joined NSUI in 2005 while studying at Zakir Hussain College. He was made the National Media Coordinator of [[NSUI]] in 2011. Thereafter, he became the National Spokesperson of [[NSUI]] in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/nsui-meet-to-mobilise-cadres-for-ls-polls-114030501177_1.html|title=NSUI meet to mobilise cadres for LS polls|date=2014-03-05|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nLooking at his impeccable credentials, Amrish was called on to become the National Media Coordinator of [[Indian Youth Congress|IYC]] in the year 2015 and holds the post since then. While being at the aforementioned position, Amrish has managed to bring talent from across the nation to his media team and is known as a great mentor amongst the team members. He was Appointed the National Spokesperson of [[Indian Youth Congress|IYC]] in 2016.\n\nAmrish was made the National Secretary of IYC in March, 2020.\n\nAmrish has also been a member of the [[All India Congress Committee]] Vichar Vibhag since 2011 and has fulfilled various responsibilities during the assembly elections in UP, Uttarakhand, Punjab, Goa and Manipur.  \n\n<br />\n\n==Mark on Governance==\nAmrish and his team have been instrumental in highlighting various problems across the nation and through their innovative campaigns, they try to highlight the issues and solutions to it. Such as, Amrish played a significant role in the National Register for Unemployment drive by the IYC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/youth-congress-launches-campaign-for-unemployment-register-807277.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandey, Amrish Ranjan}}\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder|office=Spokesperson [[Indian Youth Congress]]|\n | name               = Amrish Ranjan Pandey \n| image          =\n|alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Amrish Ranjan Pandey (Age 30)\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place        = [[Madhubani, Bihar|Madhubani]], [[Bihar]]\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = [[Politician]]\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Politician]]\n| notable_works      = \n| home_town          = \n| party              = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| website = {{URL |amrishranjanpandey.in}}\n\n}}\n'''Amrish Ranjan Pandey''' is a youth leader and is currently officiating as the National Secretary, National Media Incharge and Chief Spokesperson of the [[Indian Youth Congress]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iyc.in/About-Us/national-leadership/P42|title=National Leadership|website=iyc.in|access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> He was appointed the National Secretary of IYC in March, 2020. Along with being an active face in youth politics he is also a practising lawyer in Delhi-NCR region.\n\nHe started his political career with [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]]'s student Wing [[National Students' Union of India|NSUI]].  He has been very active in both student and youth politics at [[Indian Youth Congress|IYC]] and [[National Students' Union of India|NSUI]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/Amrish-Ranjan-Pandey|title=Amrish Ranjan Pandey: Latest News, Videos and Photos of Amrish Ranjan Pandey {{!}} Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/youth-congress-workers-detained-during-protest-over-rafale-deal-118110200837_1.html|title=Youth Congress workers detained during protest over Rafale deal|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2018-11-02|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/iyc-activists-hold-protest-demand-jaitley-s-resignation-over-mehul-choksi-issue-118102301102_1.html|title=IYC activists hold protest, demand Jaitley's resignation over Mehul Choksi issue|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2018-10-23|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2018-11-16}}proprojects. ject. KAS-CSDS study on Youth in Indian politics. s</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAmrish was born in [[Bihar]] on 25 October 1988, as son of Shri Arun kumar Pandey and Smt. Rajkumari Pandey. He traces his lineage to Shri [[Damodar Pande|Damodar pande]], who was the [[Mulkaji]] of Nepal from 1803 to 1804 and is also popularly known as the first Prime Minister of Nepal. Another significant face from Amrish's family is [[Rana Jang Pande]], who was the third Mukhtiyar or Prime Minister of Nepal. After a political conspiracy, Amrish's forefathers shifted to [[Madhubani, India|Madhubani, Bihar]] and the family has been settled there since. Having completed his primary and secondary education from [[Watson High School, Madhubani|Watson High School]], Madhubani, Amrish has strong ties with Madhubani. \n\n== Education and Leadership Training ==\nIn year 2008, Amrish completed his Bachelor's degree in Philosophy from [[Zakir Husain Delhi College|Zakir Hussain College]], University of Delhi and thereafter completed his master's degree from [[University of Delhi]]. Amrish had his first rendezvous with politics, when he joined [[National Students' Union of India|National Students Union of India]] in 2005, while studying at the Zakir Hussain College and since then he has never looked back. He is [[Bachelor of Law]] from Campus Law Center [[Delhi University]].\n\nAmrish is a political leader, not just by passion but also by formal training. He has been an active participant at various Konrad Adenauer School for Young Politicians Programme (KASYP) established by [[Konrad Adenauer Foundation]]. He was first granted a fellowship by the foundation in 2013. Since then Amrish has attended several KASYP workshops. He was also called on to attend the Legislative Fellow Program by U.S. Department of State in 2016, wherein, Amrish worked with the office of the Speaker, Columbus, [[Ohio|Ohio\ufffc]]. Thereafter, he also attended the Professional Fellows Congress (Office of Citizen Exchanges), Washington D.C. As an alumnus of [[Konrad Adenauer Foundation]], Amrish has represented India in various programs. A detailed list of the same is as follows:\n\n# Workshop on Political Parties Functions and Organisation in Democratic Societies in [[Yangon|Yongon]], Myanmar in Jan/Feb, 2013.\n# International Workshop on Youth and Politics in May, 2013 held in [[Singapore]].\n# Workshop on Local Governance and Development in August, 2013 in Singapore.\n# Workshop on Leadership Training in Campaigning and Advertising organised in the month of March, 2014 in [[Kuala Lumpur]]\ufffc.\n#Workshop on Political Party Organization and local politics in September, 2014 in [[Berlin]] and [[Erfurt]], Germany.\n#Workshop on Political Party Organization and local politics in November, 2015 in [[Davao City|Davao]].\n#KAS Young Political Leaders Caucus Meeting, 2017 for Sustainable Development Goals in [[Siem Reap|SiemReap]], Cambodia in February, 2017.\n#KAS Young Political Leaders Caucus Meeting, 2018 for Sustainable Development Goals in [[Bangkok]] in December, 2018.\n#KASYP grand Alumni meeting in the year 2019 held at [[Penang]], Malaysia.\n# \n\n==Administrative Roles ==\n# Founder and Director - '''The Democratic Mirror''' - A Unique talk show on [[Media (communication)|Media]] and [[Politics]].\n#[[Chairman|President]] - [[Center For Public Initiatives]] ([[NGO]])\n#Former [[Secretary]] - Gandhi Study Circle at [[Zakir Husain Delhi College|Zakir hussain College]]\n#Associate [[Volunteer]] - Gandhi Smriti and Darsan Samiti [[New Delhi]].\n#Amrish is also the host and Director for a weekly talk show titled \"Unveiling Political Truths\", where he hosts renowned political personalities, journalists, educationists, and academicians etc. The show has hosted several personalities so far including [[Punya Prasun Bajpai]], [[Sandeep Dikshit]], [[Vivek Tankha]], [[Rajiv Tyagi]] and [[Jaiveer Shergill]] etc.\n#Amrish and his media team also launched a nationwide oratory competition named Young India Ke Bol.\n#\n#\n#\n#\n\n==Social Contribution==\n'''Major Programmes Organized'''\n\nActed as a volunteer of an International Seminar on Cultural Diversity in South Asia organized by Zakir Husain College in collaboration with Asia Project, India International Cente\n\n==Political career==\nAmrish first joined NSUI in 2005 while studying at Zakir Hussain College. He was made the National Media Coordinator of [[NSUI]] in 2011. Thereafter, he became the National Spokesperson of [[NSUI]] in 2013.\n\nLooking at his impeccable credentials, Amrish was called on to become the National Media Coordinator of [[Indian Youth Congress|IYC]] in the year 2015 and holds the post since then. While being at the aforementioned position, Amrish has managed to bring talent from across the nation to his media team and is known as a great mentor amongst the team members. He was Appointed the National Spokesperson of [[Indian Youth Congress|IYC]] in 2016.\n\nAmrish was made the National Secretary of IYC in March, 2020.\n\nAmrish has also been a member of the [[All India Congress Committee]] Vichar Vibhag since 2011 and has fulfilled various responsibilities during the assembly elections in UP, Uttarakhand, Punjab, Goa and Manipur.  \n\n<br />\n\n==Mark on Governance==\nAmrish and his team have been instrumental in highlighting various problems across the nation and through their innovative campaigns, they try to highlight the issues and solutions to it. Such as, Amrish played a significant role in the National Register for Unemployment drive by the IYC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/youth-congress-launches-campaign-for-unemployment-register-807277.html|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{